<paragraph id="E97036DD3F61FFF6FF76FBB2FD42FBAF" blockId="84.[151,1437,1076,2038]" box="[151,674,1076,1103]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">
Size. Maximum size about 
<quantity id="2E379B383F61FFF6FE28FBB2FDF5FBAE" box="[457,533,1076,1103]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.8" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" unit="cm" value="2.8">2.8 cm</quantity>
total length.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A1D565563F61FFF6FF26FBDEFE38F817" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" type="description">
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F61FFF6FF26FBDEFBC3FAC7" blockId="84.[151,1437,1076,2038]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">
Morphology. D VI + I,6–7; A I,5–7; P 14–15. Body slender, laterally compressed. Head slightly depressed behind eyes. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F61FFF6FECBFBFAFCF1FB77" bold="true" box="[298,785,1148,1174]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Snout pointed, shorter than eye diameter</emphasis>
. Caudal peduncle slender, lower than body depth. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F61FFF6FAA6FBFAFDA1FB5B" bold="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Second dorsal and anal fins with short base</emphasis>
and low ray counts (see fin meristics). Dorsal fins of similar height, the first dorsal fin with more or less rounded margin and no elongated spines, except in breeding males that have both dorsal fins higher (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F61FFF6FEC3FB6EFDCEFAE3" author="Zander, C. D. &amp; Jelinek, H." box="[290,558,1256,1282]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" pagination="265 - 280" refId="ref66201" refString="Zander, C. D. &amp; Jelinek, H. (1976) Zur demersen Fischfauna im Bereich der Grotte von Banjole (Rovinj / YU) mit Beschreibung von Speleogobius trigloides n. gen. n. sp. (Gobiidae, Perciformes). Mitteilungen aus dem Hamburgischen Zoologischen Museum und Institut, 73, 265 - 280." type="journal article" year="1976">Zander &amp; Jelinek 1976</bibRefCitation>
; Miller 1986; Kovačić 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F61FFF6FCDBFB6FFC8EFAE3" box="[826,878,1256,1282]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">et al</emphasis>
. 2016; Engin 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F61FFF6FBF3FB6FFBA5FAE3" box="[1042,1093,1256,1282]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">et al</emphasis>
. 2017). 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F61FFF6FB47FB6EFA75FAE3" bold="true" box="[1190,1429,1256,1282]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Caudal fin truncate</emphasis>
. Scales present on body and on predorsal area, mostly not visible on photographs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F61FFF6FF26FAB6FE50F953" blockId="84.[151,1437,1076,2038]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">
Live coloration. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F61FFF6FE60FAB6FD89FAAB" bold="true" box="[385,617,1328,1354]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Body primarily red</emphasis>
(from rosy to yellow-orange to vermilion) 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F61FFF6FBAFFAB6FE14FA8F" bold="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">with series of white blotches along dorsal and ventral sides</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F61FFF6FDE0FAD2FDB2FA8F" box="[513,594,1364,1390]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1900,1924]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1876]" captionTargetId="figure-18@19.[151,1436,181,1876]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 12. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Speleogobius trigloides: A) male, B) female. Photos by R. Svensen, Selce, Croatia, Northern Adriatic Sea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601603" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601603/files/figure.png" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
), 5 irregular whitish dorsal saddles (first below first dorsal-fin origin, second (wider) at interdorsal space, third below rear second dorsal fin, fourth at about middle of caudal peduncle and fifth just before caudal-fin base); a series of 5–6 barely-defined and somewhat coalescing white to yellowish blotches along ventral profile (first on belly below first dorsal fin, last on caudal peduncle). 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F61FFF6FBC4FA46FEFAFA1F" bold="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">In males, body becoming yellow posteriorly</emphasis>
, or at least the caudal fin; white blotches often reduced, sometimes absent, especially the lower ones; dorsal fins yellowish with at least one oblique pink to light purple stripe visible on each (
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F61FFF6FB45F98EFAE7F9C3" box="[1188,1287,1544,1570]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1900,1924]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1876]" captionTargetId="figure-18@19.[151,1436,181,1876]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 12. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Speleogobius trigloides: A) male, B) female. Photos by R. Svensen, Selce, Croatia, Northern Adriatic Sea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601603" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601603/files/figure.png" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Fig. 12a</figureCitation>
). In females, background body color generally a uniform pinkish red (
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F61FFF6FCF6F9AAFC99F9A6" box="[791,889,1580,1607]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1900,1924]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1876]" captionTargetId="figure-18@19.[151,1436,181,1876]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 12. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Speleogobius trigloides: A) male, B) female. Photos by R. Svensen, Selce, Croatia, Northern Adriatic Sea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601603" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601603/files/figure.png" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Fig. 12b</figureCitation>
). Dorsal fins mostly transparent, usually with an oblique whitish stripe on each. While female colors and patterns appear to be quite constant, males may completely lose their white or pale blotches (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F61FFF6FDF4F9F2FCC0F96F" author="Zander, C. D. &amp; Jelinek, H." box="[533,800,1652,1678]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" pagination="265 - 280" refId="ref66201" refString="Zander, C. D. &amp; Jelinek, H. (1976) Zur demersen Fischfauna im Bereich der Grotte von Banjole (Rovinj / YU) mit Beschreibung von Speleogobius trigloides n. gen. n. sp. (Gobiidae, Perciformes). Mitteilungen aus dem Hamburgischen Zoologischen Museum und Institut, 73, 265 - 280." type="journal article" year="1976">Zander &amp; Jelinek 1976</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F61FFF6FCCFF9F3FC59F96F" author="Fesser, R." box="[814,953,1652,1679]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" pagination="123 - 126" refId="ref54380" refString="Fesser, R. (1980) Zusa ¨ tzliche Beschreibung von Speleogobius trigloides Zander &amp; Jelinek (1976) (Gobiidae, Perciformes), sowie neue Fundorte und Freilandbeobachtungen. Verhandlungen der Zoologisch-Botanischen Gesellschaft in Wien, 118 / 119, 123 - 126." type="journal article" year="1980">Fesser 1980</bibRefCitation>
; Miller 1986; 
